litary-Nation: New War Museums and Changing Representational Practices in Turkey since 2002 -- tContributors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aPresentations of war and violence in museums generally oscillate between the fascination of terror and its instruments and the didactic urge to explain violence and, by analysing it, make it easier to handle and prevent. The museums concerned also have to face up to these basic issues about the social and institutional handling of war and violence. Does war really belong in museums? And if it does, what objectives and means are involved? Can museums avoid trivializing and aestheticising war, transforming violence, injury, death and trauma into tourist sights? What images of shock or identification does one generate - and what images would be desirable?  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched - KU Select 2016: Backlist Collection  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aConflict. 4aCultural History. 4aExhibition. 4aMemory Culture. 4aMuseology. 4aViolence. 4aWar. 7aART / Museum Studies.2bisacsh  aConflict.  aCultural History.  aExhibition.  aMemory Culture.  aMuseology.  aViolence.  aWar.1 aBounia, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrenreich, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenz, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGryse, Piet de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHacker, Barton C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagemann